S &= 77 + 757 + 7557 + \cdots + 7 \overbrace{5 \cdots 5}^{98} 7 \\
&= 7(11 + 101 + 1001 + \cdots + \overbrace{1 \cdots 1}^{98} 1) \\
&= 7(11 + 101 + 1001 + \cdots + 10^{98} + 1).
\end{align*}
Now, let's consider the sum $T = 11 + 101 + 1001 + \cdots + 10^{98} + 1$. We can rewrite $T$ as a geometric series:
\begin{align*}
T &= 11(1 + 10 + 10^2 + \cdots + 10^{98}) \\
&= 11 \cdot \frac{10^{99} - 1}{10 - 1} \\
&= \frac{11 \cdot 10^{99} - 11}{9}.
\end{align*}
Now, we can substitute this expression for $T$ back into our expression for $S$:
\begin{align*}
S &= 7 \cdot \frac{11 \cdot 10^{99} - 11}{9} \\
&= \frac{7 \cdot 11 \cdot 10^{99} - 77}{9} \\
&= \frac{7 \overbrace{5 \cdots 5}^{99} 7 + m}{n}.
\end{align*}
Comparing the numerators, we have $7 \cdot 11 \cdot 10^{99} - 77 = 7 \overbrace{5 \cdots 5}^{99} 7 + m$, so $m = 77 - 7 \cdot 11 = 77 - 77 = 0$. Thus, $n = 9$.

Therefore, the final answer is $m + n = 0 + 9 = \boxed{9}$.

